        <h2>Favours</h2>
        <p class="lead">Instead of giving out favours we have decided to donate the money we would have spent to <i>Raise and Support the Poor</i>.</p>
        <p>RSP is a non-governmental organization in Cambodia. In 2012 I had the opportunity to travel to Cambodia and work with Sareth Brak, the Buddhist monk who runs the program. We spent two weeks in the village where Sareth lives and helped construct the second floor of the library for the local school. I learned many new skills in those two weeks, like how to bend wire for concrete posts while avoiding being eaten alive by the red ants who live in the bending block, or how to catch bricks as they are being tossed from the ground; after first being checked for lizards and snakes. However, I would say the most valuable thing I took from the experience was seeing a functional NGO that produced significant results and really made the most of the funding they received. Sareth’s commitment to the community was pretty darn inspiring, and I fully trust him to allocate the money to whatever area of the organization he thinks needs it most. So I can’t promise you that the money will buy new bikes for the kids in the village, or will pay for the concrete used in the construction of the new kitchen. It might go toward paying very boring and unromantic administrative costs. But wherever it ends up, it will be money well spent, and I thank you in advance for the favour you gave up to make the donation possible!</p>
        <h3>Sareth’s response:</h3>
        <blockquote>Hello Kayla,   It is nice to hear from you and thank you for your kind email. Of course, I remembered you that you and your team (Shannon, Sarah, Mo, Leslie, Katie, Candace....) have come to Cambodia since 2012. And your team have done great work building library project. The library is completed and we now open for everyone, it is very important.   Sound wonderful, you are going to get marriage in September, it is good news. On behalf of children and RSP's staffs and I would like to congratulate to both of you and we wish you all the best wishes. May your wonderful wedding bring a great happiness.   We would like to welcome to your donation to support RSP's project and we will use your donation to purchase reading books and notebooks, pens, color pencils, paper, chair, computer and other supplies in order to use in RSP's library. Thank you so much for your sponsor.   I am fine, my family and children are fine too. I will tell them about you and your wedding. They will be happy to hear from you as well.   I hope you and your family are doing fine, and you well prepare for your wonderful wedding.
        Kind regards, <cite>Sareth</cite></blockquote>
